{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8c4f364f-8661-4a01-820f-5a1aa35e49e8","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **implicit span conversions** into overload resolution. When the compiler sees `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, it now prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\nover the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\nbecause `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is now an applicable implicit conversion. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees. The expression tree interpreter throws at runtime when it encounters this method binding.\n\n## How to fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler selects the `Enumerable` overload. Either:\n\n**Option A – Explicit static call:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\n**Option B – Cast the receiver to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nBoth force the compiler back to the `IEnumerable<T>`-based overload, which expression trees (and the interpreter) handle fine.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"418be53f-d8a0-4cd3-89eb-f57cde87feb4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `preferInterpretation: true`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's been a change in how `Enumerable.Contains()` is resolved.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe issue is probably related to how `Enumerable.Contains` gets resolved for arrays in expression trees—