ds... no wait, `Contains` on `ICollection<int>` IS an instance method but you access it through the interface. When you have `int[] array`, `array.Contains(x)` goes through extension method resolution because `Array` doesn't directly expose a `Contains` instance method.\n\nOK, I'm fairly confident the answer is about the **span overload resolution change**. In C# 14 / .NET 10, the compiler now prioritizes `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` when calling on arrays, since there's an implicit conversion from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` that factors into extension method resolution. This breaks expression trees because they either can't compile when the compiler detects spans aren't representable, or they fail at runtime when the interpreter encounters the span-based call. The workaround is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the old behavior. at this more carefully - the C# spec for expression trees says that if the lambda body contains something that can't be represented as an expression tree, it's a compile-time error. So if the compiler resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (which involves `ReadOnlySpan<T>`), it should be a **compile-time error**.\n\nThe user says \"throws at runtime\" - this might be imprecise language, or there might be a different mechanism at play.\n\nAlternatively, maybe in C# 14, the compiler is smart enough to still emit the expression tree but references the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` method, and then at runtime, when you try to `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`, the interpreter throws because it can't handle the span-based method.\n\nI think the core issue is that C# 14's improved overload resolution now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` due to implicit span conversions, but expression trees can't represent ref struct types like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`